This numerical instability directly undermines the quality of the low-rank approximation, leading to poor gradient propagation and degraded model performance, particularly in long sequences where attention patterns are sparse or hierarchical. Standard regularization (e.g., Tikhonov) often fails because it distorts the semantic structure of attention, which is critical for tasks like reasoning or translation.

One promising mitigation strategy could involve *geometry-aware sampling* of the landmark rows/columns using determinantal point processes (DPPs) or leverage scores from randomized SVD, ensuring that the selected submatrix has maximal volume—thereby improving invertibility. Alternatively, we might explore *structured perturbation* of the intersection matrix via learned bias terms trained end-to-end to stabilize inversion without sacrificing expressivity.

Another innovative angle is to replace direct inversion with an implicit layer formulation: treat the solution of the linear system in the skeleton decomposition as a fixed-point iteration, differentiating through it via implicit differentiation. This would allow backpropagation while avoiding explicit inversion, effectively sidestepping the instability.

We could also investigate hybrid decompositions that blend skeleton factorization with orthogonal components (e.g., interpolative decomposition + QR refinement), trading off pure interpretability for numerical robustness.

Given our team’s strength in both theoretical machine learning and systems-level optimization, this topic offers dual impact: advancing the mathematical foundations of attention approximation while enabling more reliable and scalable models. It aligns well with the growing interest in *efficient transformers* and *theoretical understanding of low-rank approximations*—a sweet spot for high-impact publications and real-world deployment.
